title: Cat vs Dog
author: natalie
text: what outsiders do not understand is that we are not just infatuated worshippers at the shrine of the cat.  we can scold our cats (not that it ever does anyone any good),  laugh at our cats,  play with them,  find faults with them,  and be exasperated by their unpredictable moods.  the only thing we cannot do is to live without them.   so,  in compiling a book for other cat-lovers,  i have tried to present the cat in all moods; to show him as a cunning rascal with a nice sense of humour…; as a creature of infinite resources and courage… ; as the victim of his own perversity…; as the disciple of witchcraft; as an animal for the loss of whom a child will shed tears of inconsolable grief; the cat in fable,  superstition,  comedy,  tragedy; the cat we all know and can never fully understand.

title: Tropicial Sensation
author: nicky
text: imagine yourself in a tropical rainforest barefooted.  you see trees as big as skyscrapers.   you could see vines everywhere,  a three toed sloth hanging lazily,  a mysterious monkey popping everywhere curiously looking at you.  you can smell the aroma of mangos,  the bark of a yucca tree,  and the everlasting flowers that coated the rainforest.  you can hear the birds humming gracefully along to the beat that always went on in the rainforest the monkeys screeching and a furious roar of a puma.  you feel the small driblets of rain coating your skin,  you feel the soft tender soil against my feet.  to you it was a tropical sensation!

title: Winter Wonderland

title: Lightning
author: oriana
text: lightning seems to cause peril and destruction yet you only flash the warning of a storm.   in the blink of an eye you vanish,  leaving frightened expressions and scars of brilliant white light.   you are so quick and energetic with positives and negatives zig-zagging throughout your body.   as you recede  back into your fortress of cumulonimbus,  you let out an exhausted roar-breathing your ''boom'' of the final sign of the skies breaking.   soon afterward,  soft droplets of rain will fall from the now hushed stratus,  which will lull children to sleep,  bathe sun-bleached lawns,  and give sweet beverages to plants,  like arnold palmers served on a silver platter.   no more will the pale faces worry for the rain has come and the lightning has passed.   sadly,  you will only come again to give us the live news story of the future water puddles and drowned worms.   and although people dread and don't care,  once and a while they look up,  smile,  and exclaim- ''that's your answer.  it won't be long now. ''

text: they watch our world fading,  they see our world dying.  can they survive through this time of fright?  a candy-filled dream,  a room full of toys.  only when they sleep do they observe beauty.   where can they look? the world is so daunting.  this is a time  of dread and nightmare.   the world of us- the world of children we do not understand.  we cannot see why this world is crashing.   what can we give back to the world alone? what can we do so we wouldnâ’t have to live in obscurity?  is the answer easy? is it simple to find? here it is inside our minds.   peace.   itâ’s that easy.  hope.   itâ’s that simple.  joy.   itâ’s that effortless

title: Teddy
author: rachel
text: teddy.  a stuffed bear.  he resembles pure love,  deep enough to seek a place throughout my heart.  he looks at me as if i'm where all of his love is,  and i gaze at him that way,  too.   teddy.   soft,  matted fur,  where i've clutched him in the gloomy night.  two deep eyes hidden by bushes of fur.  floppy,  black legs supporting him.   teddy.   he cheers me when i'm blue,  he never says anything mean,  and he never will.  i trust him.   teddy.   all the love i will ever find.   the only stuffed bear i can count on.
